            "col_dk": "12",
            "col_tb": "12",
            "text_size": "40,15",
            "txt_align": "start",
            "sub_heading": "",
            "heading": "One Saree, 30 Drapes: A Minimalist Fashion Diary - Tribal Drapes",
            "text": "<p>Let’s take a break from the usual pleats and pins. Today, we’re going back — way back — to the roots of how sarees were once worn by women who didn’t need a blouse, a petticoat, or a designer label to command attention. They just needed a piece of cloth, their strength, and a way to wrap it around themselves that made sense for <strong>life in motion</strong>.</p><p>Welcome to Day 6 of my <em>One Saree, 30 Drapes</em> challenge. And today, we’re diving into the world of <strong>tribal drapes</strong>.</p><h2>Why Tribal? Why Now?</h2><p>Because tribal drapes are raw, powerful, and <strong>liberating</strong>. No frills, no fuss — just function meeting form most strikingly.</p><p>In a world obsessed with neat pleats and matching bangles, tribal drapes are a <strong>rebellion</strong>. They're wild. They're earthy. They're worn by women who farm, fight, climb, dance, carry babies on their backs, and still look like walking poetry.</p><p>And here's the thing — these drapes aren’t just beautiful. They’re practical. They move with you, not against you.</p>",
            "subhd_color": "#222222",
            "hd_color": "#222222",
            "des_color": "#878787",
            "use_shadow": false,
